name: Marcellus Williams
summary: Several legal challenges and appeals are underway to prevent the imminent execution of Marcellus Williams, a Missouri death row inmate who maintains his innocence. The Missouri Supreme Court has declined to halt the execution, while Governor Mike Parson has rejected a clemency petition. The Innocence Project claims to have discovered evidence of racial bias in jury selection and has appealed to the Supreme Court for a stay. Advocates for Williams argue that his execution would be a modern-day lynching. Various organizations and individuals, including the Missouri Independent and the Kansas City Star, are urging the courts and the governor to intervene to prevent the execution of a potentially innocent man. CBS News and USA Today have also reported on the case, highlighting the lack of DNA evidence linking Williams to the murder weapon.

name: California banning plastic bags
summary: California has passed a groundbreaking law prohibiting all plastic bags at grocery stores, making it the first state in the nation to ban both single-use and reusable plastic bags. This move comes after a previous attempt to ban plastic bags backfired. The new law, signed by Governor Gavin Newsom, aims to reduce plastic pollution and encourage the use of more sustainable options such as paper bags or reusable bags brought by customers. The ban will take effect in 2025, giving businesses and consumers time to adjust. This law is part of a broader effort by California to tackle plastic waste and protect the environment.
